(418, 1, '2015-08-07 11:06:55', '2015-08-07 11:06:55', 'The great scientist, Albert Einstein has rightly said,\r\n\r\nCompound Interest is the 8<sup>th</sup>Â  wonder of the world . . . .\r\nHe who understands it, earns it . . . .\r\nHe who doesnâ€™t . . . pays it\r\n\r\n\r\nThe number of years for which money is invested has a compounding effect on the final amount. It means that it is not the amount of money invested today but the time period for which it is invested is more important. The following example will illustrate this â€“\r\n\r\nTwo colleagues â€˜Aâ€™ and â€˜Bâ€™ are both aged 40 years. A makes an investment of Rs.5,00,000/- towards his retirement corpus at the age of 40 years. 10 years later, B invests Rs. 10,00,000/- towards his retirement corpus.Â  Both earn an interest of 12% on their investment. At the age of 60, their retirement corpus will be as follows:-\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<table width="100%" cellspacing="5" cellpadding="5">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000;" width="213"></td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213"><strong>Investor A</strong></td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213"><strong>Investor B</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000;padding-left:5px;" width="213">Amount Invested</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">Rs. 5,00,000/-</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">Rs. 10,00,000/-</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000;padding-left:5px;" width="213">Tenure</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">20Â Â Â Â  Years</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">10 years</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000;padding-left:5px;" width="213">Rate of Interest</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">12%</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">12%</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000;padding-left:5px;" width="213">Retirement Corpus</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">Rs. 48,23,147/-</td>\r\n<td style="border: 1px solid #000000; text-align: center;" width="213">Rs. 31,05,848/-</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nIt is clear from the above that Aâ€™s retirement corpus is worth 55% more than Bâ€™s. This is inspite of the fact that the amount invested by A is less than Bâ€™s. This proves that due to the power of compounding, the benefit of investing early (albeit in small amount) outweigh the amount invested.', 'The Magical Power of Compounding', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-magical-power-of-compounding', '', '', '2015-08-07 11:06:55', '2015-08-07 11:06:55', '', 0, 'http://webphics.com/wordpress/wp_dalmiablog/?p=418', 0, 'post', '', 0),
